## Checkpoint: Reading and Debugging a Real Feature

Below is a to-do list "add item" feature — the kind of code you would find in a real web application. It has **two bugs** hidden in it. Your job is to read the code, understand what it is supposed to do, and find the problems.

```javascript
let addBtn = document.getElementById('add-btn');
let input = document.getElementById('todo-input');
let list = document.getElementById('todo-list');
let counter = document.getElementById('item-count');
let items = [];

addBtn.addEventListener('click', addItem);

function addItem() {
  let text = input.value;

  if (text === '') {
    document.getElementById('error').textContent = 'Please enter a task.';
    return;
  }

  document.getElementById('error').textContent = '';
  items.push(text);

  let li = document.createElement('li');
  li.textContent = text;
  li.addEventListener('click', function() {
    li.classList.toggle('completed');
  });
  list.appendChild(li);

  counter.textContent = `${items.length} items`;
}
```

Take a moment to read through this code. Use the line-by-line strategy from Module 3.4:
1. What elements does it find on the page?
2. What happens when the button is clicked?
3. What does the function do step by step?
4. What is missing or wrong?

